{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c600a522-dac2-4d30-9416-bb41e3e33e9f","content":"The report confirms the overhead is from MSBuild **process startup and project re-evaluation** on every `dotnet build` invocation — not from actual compilation. Visual Studio avoids this by keeping a long-lived MSBuild server process. Here are the fixes, from biggest impact to smallest:\n\n### 1. Enable the MSBuild Server (biggest win)\nSet this environment variable to keep MSBuild nodes warm between CLI invocations:\n```bash\nexport DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1\n```\n\n### 2. Enable node reuse\nCreate a `Directory.Build.rsp` file so every CLI build automatically reuses MSBuild worker nodes:","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_01QenphZfJPned91ymC75S3T","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating build optimization files"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_01E2n6tMEPx4rfY9e5LGqyS8","name":"create","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-09e5b75e61024590be7c0ed547b58cd6/Directory.Build.rsp","file_text":"/nodeReuse:true\n"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"create a new file at /tmp/sv-09e5b75e61024590be7c0ed547b58cd6/Directory.Build.rsp."}],"interactionId":"0e6723dd-ad32-45e8-8980-3f544e4d40f9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The developer is experiencing slow CLI builds with `dotnet build` for incremental builds. The issue is that even when nothing has changed, CLI builds take 2-4 seconds due to MSBuild process startup and re-evaluation of the project graph on every invocation.\n\nThe key insight here is that Visual Studio keeps an MSBuild server process running (warm), which avoids the startup cost. The CLI, by default, starts a new MSBuild process each time.\n\nThe main recommendations:\n\n1. **Use the MSBuild Server** (`dotnet build -nodeReuse:true` or set `DOTNET_CLI_DO_NOT_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=0`). \n\nStarting with .NET 8, there's a built-in MSBuild server that keeps worker nodes alive between builds, which is the biggest performance win. I can enable this with the `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER` environment variable set to `1`.\n\n2. **Use `dotnet watch`** for the inner loop - it keeps the build process warm and watches for changes.\n\n3. For MSBuild node reuse, I should add `/nr:true` or set `MSBuildNodeReuse=true` to keep worker processes alive between builds and eliminate startup costs.\n\n4. I can create a `Directory.Build.rsp` file with `/nr:true` to automatically enable node reuse across all CLI builds in the project.","outputTokens":939},"id":"a0d039b2-d95d-467a-8221-913c89fdf257","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:51:48.942Z","parentId":"7cd18ec8-0df4-4e7d-8263-10084afb4314"}
