{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9a4bebf0-c30b-4509-81c0-5f12ec1e3ebc","content":"### 3. Use `dotnet watch` for the inner loop\nInstead of manually running `dotnet build` after each edit:\n```bash\ndotnet watch build\n```\nThis keeps the build process warm and auto-rebuilds on file changes — closely matching the VS experience.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Cause | Fix | Expected Impact |\n|---|---|---|\n| Cold MSBuild process start | `DOTNET_CLI_USE_MSBUILD_SERVER=1` | ~1-2s saved |\n| Worker nodes restart each time | `Directory.Build.rsp` with `/nodeReuse:true` | ~0.5-1s saved |\n| Manual rebuild cycle | `dotnet watch build` | Eliminates idle re-invocation entirely |\n\nThe `Directory.Build.rsp` file I created will apply `/nodeReuse:true` automatically to every `dotnet build` invocation in this directory tree — no developer workflow change needed. Combined with the MSBuild server env var (add it to your shell profile), incremental no-op builds should drop from 2-4s to under 1s.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0e6723dd-ad32-45e8-8980-3f544e4d40f9","outputTokens":255},"id":"d900e239-8170-40ec-bcd2-d8e0478d89d4","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:51:56.516Z","parentId":"8a40826d-d7c3-4ce4-b499-5bc975dd4c23"}
